Section section_02 (Chars 8845–12774):
Section Summary: Herbert Spencer's philosophy was shaped by his early writings in the Nonconformist, which marked a shift from his life as an engineer to a life of philosophical inquiry. His work emphasized the universality of law and the concept of evolution, which he saw as a fundamental principle governing all aspects of life, from matter to mind. Spencer's philosophy was all-inclusive, encompassing biology, psychology, sociology, and ethics, and he sought to interpret all phenomena in terms of matter, motion, and force. He believed that even mental evolution could be explained in terms of the redistribution of matter and motion, and that consciousness could be resolved into units of consciousness that are ultimately connected to physical reality. Ultimately, Spencer's philosophy acknowledged the limits of human understanding, recognizing that some mysteries, such as the ultimate reality, may be beyond human comprehension.
